WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.000
This is Jacob's Research Journal. Today's deep dive: The Real

00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:08.000
Productivity Revolution. So here's a scene you've definitely lived through.

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.000
You sit down at your desk, and everything just works.

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:16.000
The email you've been avoiding for three days writes itself.

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:20.000
That spreadsheet that made you want to scream yesterday? Suddenly

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:24.000
it makes sense. You're knocking out tasks like you're speed-running

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:28.000
your own life. Then the next morning, you sit down

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:32.000
in the exact same chair. Open the exact same laptop.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:36.000
Pour the exact same coffee. And you can't remember how

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:40.000
paragraphs work. What happened? Nothing in your environment changed. Your

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:44.000
skills didn't evaporate overnight. Your tools are identical. But something

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:48.000
shifted inside your skull, and it turns out that shift

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:52.000
is worth about eighty minutes of productive work. That number

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:56.000
comes from a study published in Science Advances by researchers

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:00.000
at the University of Toronto Scarborough. And it landed in

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:04.000
the same month as a completely different study, from Stanford,

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:08.000
that found A-I is making people dramatically more efficient at

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:12.000
life's tedious tasks, but, and this is the kicker, people

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:16.000
are spending all that freed-up time on Instagram. Together, these

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:20.000
two papers tell a story that nobody in Silicon Valley

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:24.000
is talking about. The real productivity revolution isn't about which

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:28.000
jobs A-I will replace. It's about what actually makes humans

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:32.000
productive in the first place, and what they choose to

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:36.000
do when they get time back. Let's start with the

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:40.000
brain. Cendri Hutcherson, an associate professor of psychology at U

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:44.000
of T Scarborough, and her collaborator Daniel Wilson tracked one

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:48.000
hundred and eighty-four students over twelve weeks. But here's what

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:52.000
makes this study different from the usual productivity research. They

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:56.000
weren't comparing one person to another. They tracked the same

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:00.000
individuals, day after day, watching how daily fluctuations in mental

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:04.000
sharpness predicted whether they'd actually follow through on their intentions.

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:08.000
The core finding? When a person's mental sharpness was at

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:12.000
its peak, they got the equivalent of about forty extra

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:16.000
minutes of productive work done. When sharpness was at its

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:20.000
worst, they lost about forty minutes. That's an eighty-minute swing

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:24.000
between your best day and your worst day. And here's

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:28.000
the thing that should make every self-help guru nervous: it

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:32.000
has nothing to do with willpower, personality, or self-discipline. Stable

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:36.000
personality traits like self-control and conscientiousness did not protect against

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:40.000
these daily fluctuations. The most disciplined person in the study

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:44.000
still had foggy days that cost them nearly an hour

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:48.000
of output. Mental sharpness is a daily variable, not a

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:52.000
character trait. As Hutcherson put it, "Everybody has good days

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:56.000
and bad days. What we're capturing is what separates those

00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:00.000
good days from the bad ones." So what separates them?

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:04.000
Three things, the data showed. Sleep quality. Burnout avoidance. And

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:08.000
depressive states. Not apps. Not productivity systems. Not A-I copilots.

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:12.000
Sleep, rest, and mental health. The boring stuff. The stuff

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:16.000
nobody raises a five hundred million dollar Series C to

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:20.000
solve. Think about what this means in practical terms. Every

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:24.000
company in the world is spending billions on tools to

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:28.000
make workers more efficient. Project management software, A-I assistants, workflow

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:32.000
automation. Meanwhile, the single biggest lever on daily human output

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:36.000
is whether someone slept well and isn't burning out. It's

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:40.000
like installing a supercharger on a car that has a

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:44.000
flat tire. Now here's where it gets interesting. Because at

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:48.000
the same time Hutcherson was measuring the inside of people's

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:52.000
heads, a team at Stanford's Institute for Economic Policy Research

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:56.000
was measuring what people actually do with A-I tools at

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:00.000
home. The Stanford study, authored by Michael Blank, Gregor Schubert,

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:04.000
and Miao Ben Zhang, tracked the browsing behavior of over

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:08.000
two hundred thousand U-S households from twenty twenty-one to twenty

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:12.000
twenty-four, before and after ChatGPT's release. They used pre-ChatGPT browsing

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:16.000
patterns to instrument actual adoption, then watched what happened to

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:20.000
how people spent their time online. The headline finding is

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:24.000
genuinely impressive. ChatGPT users became seventy-six to one hundred and

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:28.000
seventy-six percent more efficient at what the researchers call digital

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:32.000
chores. The tedious but necessary tasks of modern life. Job

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:36.000
hunting. Travel planning. Shopping for necessities. Paying bills. Researching health

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:40.000
questions. The stuff that eats your Sunday afternoon. That one

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:44.000
hundred and seventy-six percent figure for job hunting is remarkable.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:48.000
It means something that used to take an hour now

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:52.000
takes roughly twenty-two minutes. Travel planning that consumed an evening

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:56.000
gets done in a fraction of the time. This is

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:00.000
a genuine, measurable quality of life improvement. The kind of

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:04.000
thing that, if a pharmaceutical company discovered it, would be

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:08.000
on the cover of every magazine. But the study doesn't

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:12.000
stop at the efficiency gains. It also tracks what people

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:16.000
do with the time they save. And this is where

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:20.000
the glass cracks. Here's how Michael Blank framed it in

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:24.000
the Stanford Report. Quote, "The glass-half-full view is that Gen-A-I

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:28.000
helps people be more efficient at tedious home tasks. The

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:32.000
glass-half-empty view is that they don't seem to be spending

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:36.000
their additional free time on developing new skills." End quote.

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:40.000
People spent the time they saved on Instagram. On Netflix.

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:44.000
On socializing. Not on learning new skills, not on education,

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:48.000
not on the kind of self-improvement that might protect them

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:52.000
in an A-I disrupted labor market. They used the most

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:56.000
powerful productivity tool in human history to get chores done

00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:00.000
faster so they could scroll more. There's a third finding

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:04.000
in the Stanford data that deserves its own moment: the

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:08.000
adoption gap. Younger, higher-income households adopted ChatGPT dramatically faster than

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:12.000
older, lower-income ones. The efficiency gains are real, but they're

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:16.000
accruing unevenly. If A-I makes you one hundred and seventy-six

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:20.000
percent better at job hunting but you're not using A-I,

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:24.000
you're not just missing out on a convenience. You're falling

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:28.000
behind everyone who is. This is the digital divide rewritten.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:32.000
Now zoom out and put these two papers together, because

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:36.000
they form a single, uncomfortable picture of human productivity in

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:40.000
twenty twenty-six. On one side, the Toronto study shows that

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:44.000
the biggest daily variable in your output isn't your tools

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:48.000
or your habits. It's your neurochemistry. Sleep, burnout, mood. The

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:52.000
stuff that doesn't have an app store listing. On the

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:56.000
other side, the Stanford study shows that when we do

00:06:56.000 --> 00:07:00.000
get powerful tools that genuinely save time, we don't reinvest

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:04.000
that time productively. We reinvest it in leisure. Which isn't

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:08.000
inherently bad, people are allowed to relax. But it does

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:12.000
quietly demolish the narrative that A-I tools will naturally upskill

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:16.000
the workforce. Put them together and you get this: the

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:20.000
binding constraint on human productivity was never the tools. It's

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:24.000
the human. And the context for all of this is

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:28.000
almost comically ironic. Yesterday, Axios published a piece called "We've

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:32.000
been warned," reporting that A-I agents have erased two trillion

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:36.000
dollars from public software stocks in ten weeks. The A-I

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:40.000
industry is simultaneously warning about superintelligence and watching the market

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:44.000
price in a world where software gets eaten by its

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:48.000
own product. And while all that drama unfolds, two quiet

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:52.000
research teams discovered that the real productivity story of twenty

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:56.000
twenty-six is: sleep better, and also people use ChatGPT to

00:07:56.000 --> 00:08:00.000
book flights faster so they can watch more Netflix. That's

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:04.000
not a failure. It might actually be the most human

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:08.000
outcome imaginable. We built the most powerful cognitive tool in

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:12.000
history and immediately used it to free up time for

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:16.000
the things we actually wanted to be doing all along.

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:20.000
The productivity revolution is real. It's just not going where

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:24.000
the V-Cs expected. So what do you do with this?

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:28.000
If you're a manager, the Toronto study is the one

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:32.000
to read. Forget the productivity software procurement cycle. Ask whether

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:36.000
your people are sleeping. Ask whether they're burning out. The

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:40.000
return on investment on those questions dwarfs any SaaS license.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:44.000
If you're an individual, the Stanford study is a mirror.

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:48.000
A-I is saving you real time on real tasks, which

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:52.000
is great. But what are you doing with that time?

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:56.000
That's not a judgment. It's a genuine question, and your

00:08:56.000 --> 00:09:00.000
answer might matter more than which A-I model you're using.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:04.000
And if you're an investor or a policymaker watching the

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:08.000
A-I space, the most important productivity data of the year

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:12.000
didn't come from an earnings call or a benchmark. It

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:16.000
came from a psychology lab in Toronto and a browsing-data

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:20.000
study at Stanford. The revolution is happening. It's just quieter,

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:24.000
weirder, and more human than anyone predicted. That's the Real

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:28.000
Productivity Revolution deep dive. Full post and sources at jacobbrooke95

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:32.000
dot github dot i-o slash jacobs research journal. Thanks for

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:32.400
listening.
